      "writtenOn": "2018-05-01T22:32:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I\u0027m a little fuzzy on the reason it\u0027s useful too. There\u0027s only one port per job/process/thread, so it\u0027s not really a dispatch thing. The only use I can think of is that if you had registered on a bunch of things (i.e. your job, your process, and all your threads) you could use a different key for each to distinguish between them.\n\n...\n\nReading over https://fuchsia.googlesource.com/zircon/+/HEAD/docs/exceptions.md again, I think the idea might be you could be that you might be using the wait loop on the port as a general message handler loop. Then, the key can tell you that it\u0027s an exception.\n\nSo... I think you\u0027re probably right, maybe kSystemExceptionPortKey is probably a better name, since it\u0027s intended to be registering for the system\u0027s exceptions as per devmgr. (On the other hand, it could also probably just be kMagicKey at this point.)",
